import sqlite3
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
#Part 1
#Problem 1
sqlite_file = 'lahman2014.sqlite'
conn = sqlite3.connect(sqlite_file)
query = "with total_payroll as (SELECT teamID, yearID, sum(salary) as payroll FROM Salaries GROUP BY teamID, yearID) SELECT Teams.teamID, Teams.yearID, Teams.lgID, payroll, franchID, rank, W, G, ((W * 1.0 / G) * 100) as win_percentage FROM total_payroll, Teams WHERE total_payroll.yearID = Teams.yearID and total_payroll.teamID = Teams.teamID"
problem_1 = pd.read_sql(query, conn)
oproblem1 = pd.read_sql(query, conn)
problem_1
#The following code queries the sqlite file for the data that we need to make the plots later on
#After, we use Pandas.read_sql to transform the data from the query into a Pandas DataFrame

#There was a lot of missing data with this query. The salary data only exists for 1985-2014,
#while the teams data exists from 1871-2014. As a result, we have 
#can only query data where these two conditions join. The last statement checks if the payroll and Teams columns have the same ID, which essentially checks if
#There is actual data for those columns, all other teams are not added to the new table.

#Problem 3
currYear = 1990
currSum = 0
currNum = 0
problem_3 = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['yearID', 'avgPayroll'])
for index, row in problem_2.iterrows():
    if problem_2.at[index, 'yearID'] == currYear:
        currSum = currSum + problem_2.at[index, 'payroll']
        currNum = currNum + 1
    else:
        problem_3.loc[len(problem_3.index)] = [int(currYear), currSum / currNum]
        currSum = 0
        currNum = 0
        currYear = problem_2.at[index, 'yearID']
        currSum = currSum + problem_2.at[index, 'payroll']
        currNum = currNum + 1

problem_3 = problem_3.astype({'yearID': int})

g = sns.barplot(x = "yearID", y = "avgPayroll", data = problem_3, color = "green")
g.set(xlabel = 'Year', ylabel = 'Average Payroll', title = 'Average Payroll of Different Teams Over Time')
g = sns.set(rc = {"figure.figsize":(40,10)})
plt.show()
plt.clf()
#The following code computes the average payroll for teams over each year using a for loop over iterrows() and uses seaborn to createa a bar graph

#The graph shown illustrates the average payroll of teams increasing overtime

problem_1['years'] = pd.cut(problem_1.yearID, bins = [1985, 1991, 1997, 2002, 2008, 2014], include_lowest = True)
problem_4 = problem_1.groupby(['years', 'teamID']).agg({'payroll': 'mean', 'win_percentage': 'mean'})
problem_4 = problem_4.dropna()
#This section groups and aggregates the data by year and teamID into the mean for payroll and win percentage

#These five data frames are used to simplify the process of making scatterplots for each time period
for row in problem_4.index:
    if row[0].left == 1984.999:
        first.loc[len(first.index)] = [row[1], problem_4.loc[row].payroll, problem_4.loc[row].win_percentage]
        if row[1] == "OAK":
            OAK1 = (problem_4.loc[row].payroll, problem_4.loc[row].win_percentage)
    elif row[0].left == 1991.0:
        second.loc[len(second.index)] = [row[1], problem_4.loc[row].payroll, problem_4.loc[row].win_percentage]
        if row[1] == "OAK":
            OAK2 = (problem_4.loc[row].payroll, problem_4.loc[row].win_percentage)
    elif row[0].left == 1997.0:
        third.loc[len(third.index)] = [row[1], problem_4.loc[row].payroll, problem_4.loc[row].win_percentage]
        if row[1] == "OAK":
            OAK3 = (problem_4.loc[row].payroll, problem_4.loc[row].win_percentage)
    elif row[0].left == 2002.0:
        fourth.loc[len(fourth.index)] = [row[1], problem_4.loc[row].payroll, problem_4.loc[row].win_percentage]

#Problem 5
problem_5 = oproblem1.groupby(['yearID']).agg({'payroll': ['mean','std']})
problem_1 = pd.merge(problem_1, problem_5, on = 'yearID', how = 'inner')

first = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['teamID', 'stde', 'win_percentage'])
second = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['teamID', 'stde', 'win_percentage'])
third = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['teamID', 'stde', 'win_percentage'])
fourth = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['teamID', 'stde', 'win_percentage'])
fifth = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['teamID', 'stde', 'win_percentage'])
#The data is grouped and aggregated based on year and the mean and std of the payroll
#It is then merged into the original dataframe

problem_1.columns = ['teamID', 'yearID', 'lgID', 'payroll', 'franchID', 'Rank', 'W', 'G', 'win_percentage', 'years','avg_payroll', 'stde']

for index, row in problem_1.iterrows():
    problem_1.at[index, 'stde'] = (problem_1.at[index, 'payroll'] - problem_1.at[index, 'avg_payroll']) / problem_1.at[index, 'stde']

problem_5 = problem_1.groupby(['years', 'teamID']).agg({'stde': 'mean', 'win_percentage': 'mean'})
problem_5 = problem_5.dropna()

#Here the std is calculated

for row in problem_5.index:
    if row[0].left == 1984.999:
        first.loc[len(first.index)] = [row[1], problem_5.loc[row].stde, problem_5.loc[row].win_percentage]
    elif row[0].left == 1991.0:
        second.loc[len(second.index)] = [row[1], problem_5.loc[row].stde, problem_5.loc[row].win_percentage]
    elif row[0].left == 1997.0:
        third.loc[len(third.index)] = [row[1], problem_5.loc[row].stde, problem_5.loc[row].win_percentage]
    elif row[0].left == 2002.0:
        fourth.loc[len(fourth.index)] = [row[1], problem_5.loc[row].stde, problem_5.loc[row].win_percentage]
    elif row[0].left == 2008.0:
        fifth.loc[len(fifth.index)] = [row[1], problem_5.loc[row].stde, problem_5.loc[row].win_percentage]

#The data is sorted into the five dataframes

#Problem 8
problem_1['efficiency'] = np.nan

for index, row in problem_1.iterrows():
    problem_1.at[index, 'efficiency'] = (problem_1.at[index, 'win_percentage']) - (problem_1.at[index, 'stde'] * 2.5 + 50)
    
problem_8 = problem_1.loc[problem_1['teamID'].isin(['OAK', 'BOS', 'NYA', 'ATL', 'TBA'])]
